---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout>
	<h3 id="projects-heading">Projects</h3>
	<p>
		A list of personal projects that I've worked on, categorized by type.
		This is not an exhaustive list of all my work, but rather a selection of
		projects that I find interesting or representative of my skills and
		interests.
	</p>

	<h4>Web Applications</h4>
	<p>
		Having spent the majority of my professional career in web development,
		I have worked on a variety of web applications, both personal and
		professional. Below are some of the personal projects that I've
		developed, showcasing my skills in front-end development, design, and
		user experience.
	</p>
	<ul aria-label="Web application projects">
		<li>
			<article>
				<h5>
					<a href="https://github.com/glennpai/hideout-helper">
						Hideout Helper
					</a>
				</h5>
				<h6>What It Is</h6>
				<p>
					A web application built with Angular (originally Angular 14,
					recently updated to Angular 21) that uses browser local
					storage for persistence.
				</p>
				<h6>What It Does</h6>
				<p>
					Hideout Helper helps manage hideout resources in Escape from
					Tarkov, allowing users to track hideout progress and plan
					resource allocation. The project started as a personal tool
					and later became useful to several friends.
				</p>
				<h6>What I Learned</h6>
				<p>
					I gained experience in front-end development, state
					management, responsive UX design, and the value of iterative
					development with user feedback. If I were to continue
					development, I would focus on making the data sources more
					robust to aid long-term maintenance and reliability.
				</p>
			</article>
		</li>
		<li>
			<article>
				<h5>
					<a href="https://github.com/glennpai/gradient-tool">
						Gradient Tool
					</a>
				</h5>
				<h6>What It Is</h6>
				<p>A simple stateless web application built with Angular 12.</p>
				<h6>What It Does</h6>
				<p>
					Gradient Tool generates random color gradients from a
					user-provided base color and returns hex codes so the
					gradients can be reused in design projects.
				</p>
				<h6>What I Learned</h6>
				<p>
					As an early web app project, Gradient Tool helped me learn
					Angular fundamentals (components, services, and data
					binding) and experiment with CSS and visual design
					principles.
				</p>
			</article>
		</li>
	</ul>

	<h4>Homelab</h4>
	<p>
		In addition to web development, I have a strong interest in homelab
		projects, which allow me to explore various technologies and tools in a
		hands-on manner. These projects often involve setting up and managing
		devices (both physical and virtual), networking equipment, and other
		tools to create a personal computing environment for learning and
		experimentation. This section includes projects related to homelab
		setups, configurations, and utilities that I've developed or used in my
		homelab environment. These projects demonstrate my interest in
		infrastructure, automation, and system administration.
	</p>
	<ul aria-label="Homelab projects">
		<li>
			<article>
				<h5>
					<a href="https://github.com/glennpai/k8s-workload-template">
						K8s Workload Template
					</a>
				</h5>
				<h6>What It Is</h6>
				<p>
					A Kubernetes workload template that uses Kustomize and
					Skaffold.
				</p>
				<h6>What It Does</h6>
				<p>
					K8s Workload Template provides a flexible starting point for
					deploying workloads and simplifies manifest configuration in
					my Kubernetes cluster.
				</p>
				<h6>What I Learned</h6>
				<p>
					K8s Workload Template has been a useful resource for
					learning and experimenting with Kubernetes and container
					orchestration in my homelab. The project has helped me
					understand best practices for Kubernetes manifest
					organization and deployment workflows.
				</p>
			</article>
		</li>
	</ul>

	<h4>Game Development</h4>
	<p>
		While I have not developed any full-fledged games, I have dabbled in
		video game development and created some small projects related to game
		design and development. These projects are more experimental in nature
		and serve as a way for me to explore concepts related to game mechanics,
		procedural generation, and tool development for game development. They
		are not polished or complete games, but rather prototypes and
		experiments that reflect my interest in game development and my
		willingness to explore new areas of technology.
	</p>
	<ul aria-label="Game development projects">
		<li>
			<article>
				<h5>
					<a href="https://github.com/glennpai/item-generator">
						Item Generator
					</a>
				</h5>
				<h6>What It Is</h6>
				<p>
					A Python proof-of-concept prototype for an item generator.
				</p>
				<h6>What It Does</h6>
				<p>
					Item Generator quickly generates items with different
					attributes and properties as a flexible, extensible tool for
					game-related testing and experimentation.
				</p>
				<h6>What I Learned</h6>
				<p>
					Item Generator gave me practical exploration in procedural
					generation and data management concepts for game development
					tooling.
				</p>
			</article>
		</li>
	</ul>

	<h4>Tools and Extensions</h4>
	<p>
		This section includes projects related to tools and extensions that I've
		developed or used. These projects demonstrate my interest in enhancing
		functionality, improving workflows, and creating utilities that can be
		used in various contexts. They range from browser extensions to
		command-line tools, and they reflect my willingness to explore different
		technologies and create solutions that can be used by myself and others.
	</p>
	<ul aria-label="Tools and extensions projects">
		<li>
			<article>
				<h5>
					<a href="https://github.com/glennpai/ghes-deuteranopia">
						GHES Deuteranopia Theme
					</a>
				</h5>
				<h6>What It Is</h6>
				<p>
					A custom theme for GitHub Enterprise Server (GHES) focused
					on deuteranopia accessibility.
				</p>
				<h6>What It Does</h6>
				<p>
					GHES Deuteranopia Theme modifies GHES colors to improve
					contrast and usability for users with red-green color
					blindness.
				</p>
				<h6>What I Learned</h6>
				<p>
					Through this project, I deepened my understanding of
					accessibility-focused design, including tradeoffs and
					considerations when designing for specific visual needs.
					This project also gave me practical experience in iterative
					AI-assisted design and development, exploring how agentic AI
					can be used to create and refine a design based on user
					feedback and accessibility principles. A future iteration of
					this project would focus on expanding the theme to cover
					more UI elements and extending support to other websites.
				</p>
			</article>
		</li>
		<li>
			<article>
				<h5>
					<a
						href="https://github.com/glennpai/simple-graph-etl-python"
					>
						Simple Graph ETL (Python)
					</a>
				</h5>
				<h6>What It Is</h6>
				<p>
					A Python ETL library for working with the Microsoft Graph
					API.
				</p>
				<h6>What It Does</h6>
				<p>
					Simple Graph ETL provides a flexible interface to extract
					data, transform it, and load it into other systems. The
					project began as a personal tool and later evolved into a
					library maintained by Ohio University OIT.
				</p>
				<h6>What I Learned</h6>
				<p>
					During development, I gained hands-on experience with Graph
					API integration and the practical challenges of API-based
					data integration for enterprise use. This project was my
					first experience with building a reusable library and taught
					me important lessons about API design, documentation, and
					maintenance for shared codebases.
				</p>
			</article>
		</li>
		<li>
			<article>
				<h5>
					<a href="https://github.com/glennpai/prntsc-extension">
						Prntsc Extension
					</a>
				</h5>
				<h6>What It Is</h6>
				<p>
					A Chrome extension built with JavaScript and the Chrome
					Extensions API.
				</p>
				<h6>What It Does</h6>
				<p>
					Prntsc Extension loads random images from prnt.sc. The
					project started as an academic research tool and later
					shifted to entertainment.
				</p>
				<h6>What I Learned</h6>
				<p>
					This project helped me learn browser extension fundamentals,
					including manifest files, content scripts, and background
					scripts, while experimenting with JavaScript.
				</p>
			</article>
		</li>
		<li>
			<article>
				<h5>
					<a href="https://github.com/glennpai/aruix"> Aruix </a>
				</h5>
				<h6>What It Is</h6>
				<p>A Discord bot built with Discord.js.</p>
				<h6>What It Does</h6>
				<p>
					Aruix provides fun and practical server commands, including
					coin flip, dice roll, and administrative utilities for
					Discord communities.
				</p>
				<h6>What I Learned</h6>
				<p>
					This project allowed me to explore the Discord API and learn
					key considerations in building modular, extensible bots for
					online communities. A future iteration would focus on
					creating a reusable development API and improving the bot's
					architecture for easier maintenance and feature expansion.
				</p>
			</article>
		</li>
	</ul>

	<h4>Cron Jobs</h4>
	<p>
		This section includes projects related to cron jobs, or scheduled tasks
		that run automatically at specified intervals. These projects
		demonstrate my interest in automation and my ability to create scripts
		and tools that can be used to manage and automate various tasks.
	</p>
	<ul aria-label="Cron job projects">
		<li>
			<article>
				<h5>
					<a
						href="https://github.com/glennpai/pihole-gravity-cronjob"
					>
						Pi-hole Gravity Cron Job
					</a>
				</h5>
				<h6>What It Is</h6>
				<p>A cron job script for Pi-hole gravity list maintenance.</p>
				<h6>What It Does</h6>
				<p>
					Pi-hole Gravity Cron Job automates regular updates of
					Pi-hole gravity blocklists to keep ad and tracking domain
					filtering current.
				</p>
				<h6>What I Learned</h6>
				<p>
					This project allowed me to practice automation and shell
					scripting, especially around reliability and efficiency
					considerations for scheduled jobs.
				</p>
			</article>
		</li>
		<li>
			<article>
				<h5>
					<a href="https://github.com/glennpai/humble-bundle-scraper">
						Humble Bundle Scraper
					</a>
				</h5>
				<h6>What It Is</h6>
				<p>A Python web scraper that uses Beautiful Soup.</p>
				<h6>What It Does</h6>
				<p>
					Humble Bundle Scraper scrapes Humble Bundle data (bundle
					names, descriptions, and pricing) to track current bundles
					and support potential notifications.
				</p>
				<h6>What I Learned</h6>
				<p>
					This project allowed me to explore web scraping and data
					extraction techniques and used the project as an
					automation-oriented experiment. A future iteration would
					focus on the integration of the scraper with a notification
					system to create a more complete and useful automation
					solution.
				</p>
			</article>
		</li>
	</ul>
</Layout>

<style>
	a {
		color: var(--primary-color);
	}

	h5 {
		font-size: 1.1rem;
		font-weight: 700;
		margin-bottom: 0.25rem;
	}

	h6 {
		color: var(--secondary-color);
		font-size: 1rem;
		font-weight: 600;
		margin-top: 0.5rem;
		margin-bottom: 0.25rem;
	}
</style>
